name: Y Gwcw Fach
comments: In English, The Little Cuckoo.  The tune and first verse of this song were collected in Utica, New York, USA, in 1903 from a woman who had learned it from her Welsh mother.  First published in "Alawon y Celt", a collection edited by Robert Bryan, who also added the second and third verses, in which the singer sends her true love a message, a theme often associated with songs about birds.

name: The Bonny Ship the Diamond
comments: This ballad is based on a historical incident.  Due to depletion of the whale fisheries, by the 1820s, whalers were voyaging in more treacherous waters in search of prey.  In 1830, a fleet of some 50 whalers headed to the Davis Straits in Greenland to hunt.  Almost 20 ships were smashed and splintered by ice floes in Melville Bay during this expedition, including The Diamond.  This song is collected in the Roud Folksong Index as number 2172.

name: Bad Motorcycle
comments: The original release of this song on a small local Philadelphia label, Peak, credited "Storey-Williams" as the writers/composers. The Storey Sisters sang the song and Kae Williams was a Philadelphia area disk jockey, producer, and manager who used the term "Bad Motorcycle" to describe something good or cool. When the record was released on a larger label, Cameo, the song was credited to Al Browne, who owned Peak Records and whose band played on the recording, and Frederick Williams.

name: I Wouldn't Change You if I Could
comments: Song originally recorded by country singer Jim Eanes in 1959 and credited to himself as songwriter. It was later more successfully recorded by Ricky Skaggs. The song was actually written by Arthur Q. Smith and purportedly sold to Eanes, as Smith had sold him many of his songs. Smith also sold a 1/2 share of the song to Paul H. Jones, and retained the other half. When Skaggs' recording came out it was initially credited to Eanes, but once it became a hit, Smith's widow, Lillian Pritchett, sued the publisher. As Eanes couldn't show proof he had purchased the song, the song credits were transferred out of Eanes' name over to Smith's estate and Jones. Eanes went to his grave attesting that he actually wrote the song.

comments: In 1864, George Washington Johnson of Hamilton, Canada published the lyrics to this song. In 1866 James Butterfield set the poem to music. Flatt & Scruggs recorded an instrumental song called "Maggie Blues" that they registered as their own, but the tune is almost identical to the tune of "When You and I Were Young, Maggie" I wandered today to the hills Maggie To watch the scene below The creek and the creaking old mill Maggie Where we used to long long ago

name: Gee
comments: Bill Davis, Sonny Norton and Viola Watkins wrote this song and their names appear in the listing in the "Library of Congress Catalog of Copyright Entries" and on the early sheet music. (See attachments.)  However, when it became a surprise hit, George Goldner, head of the Rama label, needed money to promote this record nationally. Consequently, he formed an association with Morris Levy resulting in Levy acquiring part ownership of Rama, publishing rights to "Gee' and authorship credit for the song. As a result, the BMI registration for "Gee" credits only Davis and Levy.

comments: Miss McLeod's is an Irish reel tune that became better known as Hop Light (or High) Ladies in the US.  Some nonsense lyrics were added over time about an "Uncle Joe", but it's typically performed without lyrics. Versions that do include lyrics typically have these verses: Did you ever go to meeting, Uncle Joe, Uncle Joe (3x) Don't mind the weather so the wind don't blow (Chorus) Hop high ladies the cakes all dough (3x) Don't mind the weather so the wind don't blow

name: Fare Thee Well (Oh Honey) [Dink's Song]
comments: Folk song that tells the story of a woman deserted by her lover when she needs him the most. In 1904, ethnomusicologist John Lomax recorded it with his huge Edison recording machine as sung by an African American woman called 'Dink' in a tent camp of migratory levee-builders in Texas. It was published in 1934 in John and Alan Lomax's "American Ballads and Folk Songs". The Lomax recording is believed to be lost (or worn out at least). If I had wings like Noah's dove I'd fly the river to the one I love Fare thee well, my honey, fare thee well

name: Hen Wlad Fy Nhadau [Land of My Fathers] [National Anthem of Wales]
comments: The common belief, based on a 1910 letter by Taliesin James (son of James James), is that the tune "Glan Rhondda" [Banks of the Rhondda] was composed by James James one day in January 1856 as he walked along the river bank in his hometown of Pontypridd and after returning home and singing the melody to his father, Evan James wrote three verses by the following day.  There is some doubt and uncertainty, however, as to whether the words might have been written before the music.  A week later, it was performed by Elizabeth John from Pontypridd, in the vestry of Tabor Chapel, Maesteg. Over time the song gained popularity, initially in the locality but soon spreading across Wales.  The song became better known still after the 1858 Langollen Eisteddfod, after Thomas Llewelyn from Aberdare included it in a volume of unpublished Welsh airs he compiled for a competition entry.  The adjudicator, John Owen (Owain Alaw) then published the song in "Gems of Welsh Melody", published in 1860 by Isaac Clarke, Ruthin, under the title "Hen Wlad Fy Nhadau" [Land of My Fathers] from its opening line. Owain Alaw included the song in his own concert repertoire and it was adopted by other contemporary popular soloists, with notable performances by Lewis William Lewis (Llew Llwyfo) at the 1866 Chester Eisteddfod and Robert Rees (Eos Morlais) at the 1874 Bangor National Eisteddfod.  By the Caernarfon Eisteddfod of 1880, it was adopted as the Eisteddfod song and has been sung at every Gorsedd ceremony ever since.  It was increasingly sung at various patriotic gatherings and gradually developed into the Welsh national anthem.
